
Task 1 — Term Deposit Subscription Prediction (Bank Marketing)
🎯 Objective
Predict whether a bank customer will subscribe to a term deposit based on demographic info, contact history, and economic indicators using binary classification models.

⬇️ Dataset
Bank Marketing Dataset — UCI Machine Learning Repository

✅ No manual download needed!
The notebook automatically downloads the dataset from UCI in the first cell.
Just run the cells in order.

Direct link (for reference): https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/222/bank+marketing

🚀 How to Run on Google Colab
Go to colab.research.google.com
Click File → Upload Notebook and upload Task1_Bank_Marketing.ipynb
Run all cells in order (Runtime → Run All)
The first cell downloads the dataset automatically
📋 My Approach
1. Data Loading & Exploration
Downloaded Bank Marketing dataset (41,188 rows, 20 features) from UCI
Explored class distribution — found severe imbalance (~88% No, ~12% Yes)
Analyzed subscription rates by job type, education, and marital status
2. Data Preprocessing
Replaced unknown values with mode imputation
Label-encoded all categorical features (job, marital, education, etc.)
Applied StandardScaler for Logistic Regression
Used class_weight='balanced' to handle class imbalance
3. Models Trained
Model	Strategy
Logistic Regression	Baseline linear model, scaled features
Random Forest	Ensemble tree model, handles non-linearity
4. Evaluation Metrics
Confusion Matrix (True Positive, False Positive, etc.)
F1-Score (best for imbalanced datasets)
ROC-AUC Curve (overall discriminative ability)
5. Explainable AI (SHAP)
Used TreeExplainer on Random Forest
Generated global feature importance (bar + beeswarm plots)
Explained 5 individual predictions using waterfall plots
📊 Results & Findings
Model	F1-Score	ROC-AUC
Logistic Regression	~0.47	~0.79
Random Forest	~0.52	~0.80
Key Insights:

duration (call duration) is the strongest predictor — longer calls mean higher subscription probability
Economic indicators (euribor3m, emp.var.rate) heavily influence customer decisions
Random Forest outperforms Logistic Regression due to non-linear feature interactions
SHAP waterfall plots clearly show why each prediction was made (XAI transparency)
